@NODE MenusGame "mris: Menus (Game)"

                                @{b}Menus: Game@{ub}

   @{b}Change user...@{ub}

   Change user  name.  The  name  of the user  is very important for the
   highscore tables.  You can change the username at  any time, even  in
   the middle of the game.

   The game tries to find a @{" default username " LINK Defaults 17} during startup.


   @{b}Errors...@{ub}

   This menu  item opens  the error window. This window actually pops up
   automatically  in case of  an error  (unless something prevents that,
   such as an out-of-memory condition).


   @{b}About mris...@{ub}

   Display some information about the game.


   @{b}Quit@{ub}

   Many  years  of careful research have not produced any useful  result
   yet. Millions  of dollars  have been spent, but  we still don't  know
   what this item does.

@ENDNODE

@NODE MenusGardens "mris: Menus (Gardens)"

                              @{b}Menus: Gardens@{ub}

   During startup, mris scans the  directory "PROGDIR:mris gardens"  for
   garden files. The available files are listed in this menu.

   Contrary  to Xmris, mris keeps seperate sets of highscore tables  for
   every garden file.

   Note that the garden  files  used by mris are NOT compatible with the
   loadable gardens  used by Xmris.  However, I have  added a conversion
   program called @{" ASCIItoGarden " LINK ASCIItoGarden} to convert Xmris garden files to  mris
   garden files.

@ENDNODE

@NODE MenusDemos "mris: Menus (Demo screen)"

                            @{b}Menus: Demo screen@{ub}

   This menu lets you go directly to any of the game demo screens.

   Note  that  you will be able to go  to the highscore screen,  but  if
   there are no highscore  tables available to display  you'll  actually
   end up at the game name screen.

   Also, the  "Sprites"  demo screen  is different from the  other  demo
   screens. It does not  time  out, and the throw key will not start the
   game. The  "Sprites" screen is only available thru menu selection; it
   will not be displayed during normal demo cycling.

@ENDNODE

@NODE MenusSettings "mris: Menus (Settings)"

                              @{b}Menus: Settings@{ub}

   The Settings menu lets you change various aspects of the game.

   @{b}Random apples@{ub}

   (X)mris has  two methods  for placing the apples. They will either be
   placed according to one  of four sets of explicit apple positions, or
   placed randomly on any permitted location (though trying not to place
   them adjacently).
   If this option is turned "on", apples will be placed randomly.


   @{b}Control@{ub}

   @{b}Control/Joystick (port 1)@{ub}

   If this option is turned "on", the game will use a joystick connected
   to gameport 1.
   If this option is "off", the joystick will be left alone.


   @{b}Control/Key bindings...@{ub}

   Selecting  this item opens  a  window that  lets  you change  the key
   bindings.   The window contains a string gadget for every key; if the
   string gadget  is  empty,  the  default key will be  used.  Keys  are
   specified as standard commodity descriptions of class "rawkey".


   @{b}Display@{ub}

   @{b}Display/female (msit)@{ub}

   (X)mris  can  also  be  run  as msit.  The  two sexes have  different
   sprites.  Mris selects the classic sprites, while msit selects a more
   modern set.   The @{" initial gender " LINK Startup 4} of  the game  is  taken from  the
   program name (mris or msit);


   @{b}Display/Dynamic colors@{ub}

   This option enables the use of two dynamic colors, which alter during
   the game. Note that if this option is "on",  dynamic colors will only
   be used if two colors are available for exclusive use.
   If you don't understand this, don't worry. Leave it "on".


   @{b}Display/Screen...@{ub}

   Select the screen to  use  for mris.   This  item  opens a screenmode
   requester which  lets  you  select an existing  public  screen,  or a
   screenmode and size for a new screen.
   Note  that the width,  height  and depth  gadgets have no meaning for
   existing public screens.
   Also, the requester  will  only  offer public  screens that are large
   enough for the mris window.
   If you specify a new screen, the minimum size of the width and height
   gadgets is a "few pixel" too small  --- this is  because mris doesn't
   know the size of the window borders in  advance.  The minimum size is
   actually the size of the window contents, so you must make the actual
   screen a little larger.
   You can't specify a screen font, for the time being.


   @{b}Display/Font...@{ub}

   This item opens a fontrequester to let you select another font to use
   for the game. Note that we only support fonts up to 32 pixels high.
   Also, for the time  being, slanted or italic fonts are not completely
   supported  ---  the last letter in a string  might be cut off at  the
   right edge.


   @{b}Save as...@{ub}

   This item  will  open  a  filerequester to select  a file to save the
   current settings to. Settings are  always  saved  into icons;  if the
   selected filename does not  already have an  ".info"  suffix, ".info"
   will be appended.

   If the icon is actually the  program icon, the settings are  saved as
   default, as described @{" below " LINK MenusSettings 92}.

   Otherwise the selected icon  is created or  modified.  The  resulting
   icon will  be a project  icon  with the  default tool set to the game
   executable, and  @{" tooltypes " LINK WorkbenchStartup} set according to the  current settings.
   All unknown tooltypes are preserved.


   @{b}Save as default@{ub}

   This is  very similar  to  the @{" previous " LINK MenusSettings 76} menu  item, except that  it
   always writes to the program  icon. Consequently, the resulting  icon
   will be a tool icon.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Startup "mris: Startup"
@PREV Menus

                                  @{b}Startup@{ub}

   Mris can  be  run  from  workbench or  a shell.  In any case, various
   @{" defaults " LINK Defaults} are set up before program parameters are parsed.

   If,  after all arguments have been processed as described below,  the
   game still doesn't  have a  username, the @{" Change user... " LINK MenusGame 4} window  is
   automatically opened.

   @{" Workbench startup " LINK WorkbenchStartup}
   @{" Shell startup     " LINK ShellStartup}

@ENDNODE

@NODE WorkbenchStartup "mris: Workbench startup"

                             @{b}Workbench startup@{ub}

   Mris can be run from a tool or project icon. In any case, the program
   icon is  read first.  Other  icons are  read in  the order  they were
   selected.

   For project  icons,  only  the icons are  read.  If  the  project  is
   associated with a file, the file is ignored.

   The following tooltypes are supported:

   @{b}MSIT@{ub}
   @{b}MSIT=YES@{ub}

   Change the @{" game gender " LINK MenusSettings 34} to female (msit).

   @{b}MSIT=NO@{ub}

   Change the @{" game gender " LINK MenusSettings 34} to male (mris).


   @{b}USER=<user name>@{ub}

   Set the @{" username " LINK MenusGame 4} to <user name>.


   @{b}UP=<key deescription>@{ub}
   @{b}DOWN=<key deescription>@{ub}
   @{b}LEFT=<key deescription>@{ub}
   @{b}RIGHT=<key deescription>@{ub}
   @{b}THROW=<key deescription>@{ub}
   @{b}PAUSE=<key deescription>@{ub}
   @{b}QUIT=<key deescription>@{ub}
   @{b}ICONIZE=<key deescription>@{ub}

   Change the binding of the respective @{" key " LINK MenusSettings 24}.


   @{b}PUBSCREEN=<public screen name>@{ub}

   Same as SCREEN=PUBSCREEN=<public screen name>. @{" See below. " LINK WorkbenchStartup 77}


   @{b}FONT=@{" <font description> " LINK FontDescription}@{ub}

   Set the @{" font " LINK MenusSettings 67} to be used. 


   @{b}JOYSTICK@{ub}
   @{b}JOYSTICK=YES@{ub}

   Use a @{" Joystick " LINK MenusSettings 17} in gameport 1.


   @{b}JOYSTICK=NO@{ub}

   Don't use a @{" Joystick " LINK MenusSettings 17} in gameport 1.


   @{b}DYNAMIC@{ub}
   @{b}DYNAMIC=YES@{ub}

   Use @{" dynamic colors " LINK MenusSettins 42}, if possible.


   @{b}DYNAMIC=NO@{ub}

   Don't use @{" dynamic colors " LINK MenusSettings 42}, even if possible.


   @{b}RANDOM@{ub}
   @{b}RANDOM=YES@{ub}

   Place @{" apples randomly " LINK MenusSettings 6}.


   @{b}RANDOM=NO@{ub}

   Don't place the @{" apples randomly " LINK MenusSettings 6}.


   @{b}SCREEN=@{" <screen description> " LINK ScreenDescription}@{ub}

   Specifies the @{" screen " LINK MenusSettings 50} to open on.

@ENDNODE

@NODE ShellStartup "mris: Shell startup"

                               @{b}Shell startup@{ub}

   If  run from a shell, mris will read its program icon if  it  exists.
   After that, the command line is processed.

   The following command line arguments are supported:


   @{b}MSIT/S@{ub}

   Change the @{" game gender " LINK MenusSettings 34} to female (msit).


   @{b}MRIS/S@{ub}

   Change the @{" game gender " LINK MenusSettings 34} to male (mris).


   @{b}USER=USERNAME/K@{ub} <user name>

   Set the @{" username " LINK MenusGame 4}.


   @{b}UP/K@{ub} <key description>
   @{b}DOWN/K@{ub} <key description>
   @{b}LEFT/K@{ub} <key description>
   @{b}RIGHT/K@{ub} <key description>
   @{b}THROW/K@{ub} <key description>
   @{b}PAUSE/K@{ub} <key description>
   @{b}QUIT/K@{ub} <key description>
   @{b}ICONIZE/K@{ub} <key description>

   Change the binding of the respective @{" key " LINK MenusSettings 24}.


   @{b}PUBSCREEN/K@{ub} <public screen name>

   Same as @{"SCREEN" LINK ShellStartup 77}="PUBSCREEN=<public screen name>".


   @{b}FONT/K@{ub} @{" <font description> " LINK FontDescription}

   Set the @{" font " LINK MenusSettings 67} to be used. 


   @{b}JOYSTICK/S@{ub}

   Use a @{" Joystick " LINK MenusSettings 17} in gameport 1.


   @{b}NOJOYSTICK/S@{ub}

   Don't use a @{" Joystick " LINK MenusSettings 17} in gameport 1.


   @{b}DYNAMIC/S@{ub}

   Use @{" dynamic colors " LINK MenusSettins 42}, if possible.


   @{b}NODYNAMIC/S@{ub}

   Don't use @{" dynamic colors " LINK MenusSettings 42}, even if possible.


   @{b}RANDOM/S@{ub}

   Place @{" apples randomly " LINK MenusSettings 6}.


   @{b}NORANDOM/S@{ub}

   Don't place the @{" apples randomly " LINK MenusSettings 6}.


   @{b}SCREEN/K@{ub} @{" <screen description> " LINK ScreenDescription}

   Specifies the @{" screen " LINK MenusSettings 50} to open on.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Sound "mris: Sound and music"

                              @{b}Sound and music@{ub}

   Sorry.  Xmris 4.02 doesn't have sound or background tunes, and  among
   the things I cannot  possibly do is writing  music and creating sound
   effects.  Therefore, Xmris 4.02 is silent, and so is mris 1.1.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Changes "mris: Changes"

                              @{b}Recent changes@{ub}

   This  is the first release, which means no changes. However,  besides
   the obvious stuff I have fixed what I think is a bug in the  original
   Xmris 4.02.  When  the  apples  are placed  randomly  (+random),  the
   original  Xmris apparently places all  the apples at the  top of  the
   board. When I  examined that behavior I found  something that  looked
   like a typo,  and  fixed  it. There  is a  slight chance that  I have
   missed  something ---  that  some  part of  the  source  that  I have
   disabled somehow causes the apples to be placed randomly, but I don't
   really think that's the case.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Defaults "mris: Defaults"

                             @{b}Default settings@{ub}

   The  default gender is derived from the program name:  if it contains
   the string "msit" (ignoring case), the default gender will be  female
   (msit), otherwise it will be male (mris).
   The gender can be  changed with the  @{" Settings/Display/Female (msit) " LINK MenusSettings 34}
   menu  item, the  @{" MRIS/MSIT " LINK ShellStartup 10} command line arguments, or  the  @{" MSIT " LINK WorkbenchStartup 13}
   tooltype.

   The game is known as mris, because the arcade game was masculine.

   Note that  the game  only  checks the name of the executable; it does
   not consider the name of  selected project icons when determining the
   default gender.

   The game also tries to find a reasonable default  username. It checks
   the environment variables REALNAME, USERNAME and USER, in that order.
   If it finds one with at least 5 characters, that string will be  used
   as username. Otherwise no username will be set.
   The username can be changed with the @{" Game/Change User... " LINK MenusGame 4} menu item,
   the @{" USER " LINK WorkbenchStartup 23} tooltype or the @{" USER " LINK ShellStartup 20} command line argument.

   The default keys are language dependent; the english defaults are:
     up      -> up
     down    -> down
     left    -> left
     right   -> right
     throw   -> space
     pause   -> p
     quit    -> q
     iconize -> i
   The     key     bindings     can     be     changed     with      the
   @{" Settings/Control/Key binding... " LINK MenusSettings 24} menu item,  the @{" key tooltypes " LINK WorkbenchStartup 28} or
   the @{" key command line " LINK ShellStartup 25} arguments.

   The  default  screen will be  the  default public  screen,  which  is
   usually the Workbench  screen. You can specify a screen with the
   @{" SCREEN " LINK WorkbenchStartup 40} tooltype or the @{" SCREEN " LINK ShellStartup 77} command line argument.

   The  default  font  is  "Times 18", which  is  part  of  the  AmigaOS
   distribution.  If it is not available, the screenfont will be used if
   it  fits the  requirements  (i.e. has a height of  no  more  than  32
   pixels). If it doesn't, "Topaz 9" will be used.
   The font  can be changed  with the  @{" Settings/Display/Font... " LINK MenusSettings 67}  menu
   item, the @{" FONT " LINK WorkbenchStartup 45} tooltype or the @{" FONT " LINK 42} command line argument.

   Concerning the joystick, the  default is to use a joystick in port 1.
   This can  be  changed with  the @{" Settings/Control/Joystick (port 1) " LINK MenusSettings 17}
   menu item,  the @{" JOYSTICK " LINK WorkbenchStartup 50} tooltype,  or the  @{" JOYSTICK/NOJOYSTICK " LINK 47}
   command line arguments.

   The game will default  to  using dynamic colors. This can be  changed
   with the  @{" Settings/Display/Dynamic colors " LINK MenusSettings 42} menu item, the @{" DYNAMIC " LINK WorkbenchStartup 61}
   tooltype or the @{" DYNAMIC/NODYNAMIC " LINK 57} command line arguments.

   The  default  for  the  "Random  apples" option is  OFF; this can  be
   changed with  the @{" Settings/Random apples " LINK MenusSettings 6}  menu item, the  @{" RANDOM " LINK WorkbenchStartup 72}
   tooltype, or the @{" RANDOM/NORANDOM " LINK 67} command line arguments.

   If it  exists, the  garden  file "Digits" will used on startup. If it
   does not exist, no garden file will be loaded. The active garden file
   can be changed with the @{" Gardens " LINK MenusGardens} menu.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Bugs "mris: Known bugs"

                                @{b}Known bugs@{ub}

   Besides the  things implied  by  the @{" ToDo " LINK ToDo} list,  there is only  one
   known bug: currently all filerequesters "forget" their selection when
   they are closed.  This means if close a  filerequester and reopen  it
   later, it will start at its default setup again.

   Also,   not   all   combinations   of   mid-game   gender   changing,
   iconification/deiconification  and  dynamic/nodynamic  color  changes
   have been  checked. In  fact,  mid-game iconification/deiconification
   was hacked into the game, since the original Xmris doesn't need to do
   it the way it has to be done  on  the Amiga; this is probably one  of
   the major problem areas of the AmigaOS port.

   When you display a manual, some resources will not be freed until the
   game window closes (iconification, gender changing, quitting etc.).
   This  is a design or implementation bug of amigaguide.library ---  it
   doesn't seem to send any message when the window is closed, therefore
   I can't  free  the  stuff  until I  really  want  to quit.  Also, the
   AmigaGuide documentation is among the worst that  Commodore  has ever
   produced.

   Mris does not  warn  you  if a  key  is  assigned  to more  than  one
   function.

   The score tables might look really ugly if you use wide fonts, 'cause
   the game will reduce inter-column  spacing to 0. Maybe I should force
   some space between columns.

   On  screens with just a few colors, the  game might decide to run  in
   color even though it would look better in monochrome. There is really
   no easy way to fix this --- how do you measure "looks good"?
   The same problems applies to monochrome displays. If you are using an
   8-bit greyscale display, the game might come up in color. There is no
   way  to  get around  this,  since  AmigaOS  doesn't care whether  the
   display is color or greyscale --- it assumes color.
   A  future  mris  release  might  allow you  to  force  the  game into
   monochrome (Xmris has this feature).

   The screenmode requester, and the system displayinfo database, lack a
   couple of features, so the screen configuration is not as comfortable
   as it  should.  Of  course,  part of the  problem  could be solved by
   making my own screen requester,  but  most  of the technical problems
   require additional AmigaOS features.

   The  error  handling  during  startup  is  somewhat unfriendly.  This
   affects all errors that cause an abort, instead of  just  leaving  an
   iconified game.

   Not  all out of  memory conditions are actually reported in the error
   window,  although none of  them will  be fatal.   Most  out of memory
   conditions just  cause  some  things  to not work at all, or not work
   properly. This means  windows might not open, oversized text  strings
   that  would normally be  clipped  suddenly start trashing  the window
   borders  and similar  things.

   There  is  absolutely  no  (system  approved) way  to  close  an  ASL
   requester under program control. This  means any of these  requesters
   will stay open until they are closed  by the user. It also means they
   won't move to another screen.

   The area where the den is placed seems to be slightly gfx trashed.  I
   have no idea whether this is a problem that Xmris has as well. -:(

   If  you  have  created  your  own screen (instead  of  opening on  an
   existing screen), and  there are visitor windows on this screen,  and
   you change the screen for mris, mris  will  block  until all  visitor
   windows are  closed. It will block and block and block... there is no
   way (yet) to change your decision and reopen on the old screen.

   Not all "special" cases  that  the game should be able to handle have
   been tested, and some them have only had some quick testing.

@ENDNODE

