@NODE ScreenDescription "Screen description strings"

                        @{b}Screen description strings@{ub}

   Screen  description  strings are used  to describe a screen. They are
   constructed from the following template:

   PUBSCREEN/K: the name  of an existing  public screen to  open  on. If
                this argument  is given, none of the remaining arguments
                must be specified.

   LEFT/K/N:
   TOP/K/N:
   WIDTH/K/N:
   HEIGHT/K/N:  size and position of the screen

   DEPTH/K/N:   depth of screen

   TITLE/K:     title of screen

   OVERSCAN/S:  use "graphics" overscan instead of "text" overscan

   FONT/K:      a @{" font description " LINK FontDescription} string.

   MODEID/K/N:  Currently the only way to specify a mode is by supplying
                the mode-ID.  If no mode  is specified,  the mode of the
                "Workbench" screen will be used.

                The  easiest  way to  obtain  the required mode ID is by
                opening the @{" screen configuration " LINK MenusSettings 50} requester,  selecting
                the  mode you want, save  it and  examine  the  @{" SCREEN " LINK WorkbenchStartup 83}
                tooltype.


   Example:
   DEPTH=3 MODEID=167940 TITLE="mris screen"
   A  fullsize (text-overscan) PAL interlace screen with 8 colors (I use
   this  on  my  system,  since  NTSC  screens  are  too  small).

   DEPTH=2 MODEID=102404 HEIGHT=570 FONT="helvetica 18"
   A text-overscanned, standard width NTSC hires interlace screen with 4
   colors, a height of 570 pixels and "helvetica 18" as screen font.


   Note that the  screen descriptions  might look strange when specified
   as command line arguments. The  last example specified via  tooltypes
   is written as:

   SCREEN=DEPTH=2 MODEID=102404 HEIGHT=570 FONT="helvetica 18"

   However, for a command line argument you have to write:
   SCREEN="DEPTH=2 MODEID=102404 HEIGHT=570 FONT=*"helvetica 18*""

@ENDNODE

@NODE FontDescription "Font description strings"

                         @{b}Font description strings@{ub}

   Font description strings are used  to specify a bitmap font. They are
   constructed from the following template:

   NAME/A:      the name of the font
   SIZE/N/A:    the pixel height of the font

   UNDERLINE/S:
   BOLD/S:
   SLANTED/S:   font styles. Mris currently ignores these.

@ENDNODE

@NODE ASCIItoGarden

                               @{b}ASCIItoGarden@{ub}

   This is a simple converter program to convert  Xmris garden files  to
   mris garden files. It can only be used from a shell:

   ASCIItoGarden ASCIIFILE/A,GARDENFILE/A

   ASCIIFILE/A:  the xmris garden file (source file)
   GARDENFILE/A: the mris garden file (destination file)

   ASCIItoGarden  is  not very  powerful;  it will probably work for all
   files created by  xmred. It  definitely works for  the xmris  gardens
   digits.gdn, alphabet.gdn and puzzle.gdn (the gardens that are part of
   the xmris-4.02 distribution).

@ENDNODE

